T1  - The Real Effects of Credit Ratings: The Sovereign Ceiling Channel
AU  - ALMEIDA, HEITOR
AU  - CUNHA, IGOR
AU  - FERREIRA, MIGUEL A.
AU  - RESTREPO, FELIPE
Y1  - 2017/02/01
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12434
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 249
EP  - 290
VL  - 72
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12434
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We show that sovereign debt impairments can have a significant effect on financial markets and real economies through a credit ratings channel. Specifically, we find that firms reduce their investment and reliance on credit markets due to a rising cost of debt capital following a sovereign rating downgrade. We identify these effects by exploiting exogenous variation in corporate ratings due to rating agencies' sovereign ceiling policies, which require that firms' ratings remain at or below the sovereign rating of their country of domicile.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Financial Contracting and Organizational Form: Evidence from the Regulation of Trade Credit
AU  - BREZA, EMILY
AU  - LIBERMAN, ANDRES
Y1  - 2017/02/01
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12439
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 291
EP  - 324
VL  - 72
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12439
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We present evidence that restrictions to the set of feasible financial contracts affect buyer-supplier relationships and the organizational form of the firm. We exploit a regulation that restricted the maturity of the trade credit contracts that a large retailer could sign with some of its small suppliers. Using a within-product difference-in-differences identification strategy, we find that the restriction reduces the likelihood of trade by 11%. The retailer also responds by internalizing procurement to its own subsidiaries and reducing overall purchases. Finally, we find that relational contracts can mitigate the inability to extend long trade credit terms.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Buyout Activity: The Impact of Aggregate Discount Rates
AU  - HADDAD, VALENTIN
AU  - LOUALICHE, ERIK
AU  - PLOSSER, MATTHEW
Y1  - 2017/02/01
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12464
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 371
EP  - 414
VL  - 72
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12464
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Buyout booms form in response to declines in the aggregate risk premium. We document that the equity risk premium is the primary determinant of buyout activity rather than credit-specific conditions. We articulate a simple explanation for this phenomenon: a low risk premium increases the present value of performance gains and decreases the cost of holding an illiquid investment. A panel of U.S. buyouts confirms this view. The risk premium shapes changes in buyout characteristics over the cycle, including their riskiness, leverage, and performance. Our results underscore the importance of the risk premium in corporate finance decisions.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Asset Pricing with Countercyclical Household Consumption Risk
AU  - CONSTANTINIDES, GEORGE M.
AU  - GHOSH, ANISHA
Y1  - 2017/02/01
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12471
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 415
EP  - 460
VL  - 72
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12471
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We show that shocks to household consumption growth are negatively skewed, persistent, countercyclical, and drive asset prices. We construct a parsimonious model where heterogeneous households have recursive preferences. A single state variable drives the conditional cross-sectional moments of household consumption growth. The estimated model fits well the unconditional cross-sectional moments of household consumption growth and the moments of the risk-free rate, equity premium, price-dividend ratio, and aggregate dividend and consumption growth. The model-implied risk-free rate and price-dividend ratio are procyclical, while the market return has countercyclical mean and variance. Finally, household consumption risk explains the cross section of excess returns.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Local Risk, Local Factors, and Asset Prices
AU  - TUZEL, SELALE
AU  - ZHANG, MIAO BEN
Y1  - 2017/02/01
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12465
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 325
EP  - 370
VL  - 72
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12465
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Firm location affects firm risk through local factor prices. We find more procyclical factor prices such as wages and real estate prices in areas with more cyclical economies, namely, high ?local beta? areas. While procyclical wages provide a natural hedge against aggregate shocks and reduce firm risk, procyclical prices of real estate, which are part of firm assets, increase firm risk. We confirm that firms located in higher local beta areas have lower industry-adjusted returns and conditional betas, and show that the effect is stronger among firms with low real estate holdings. A production-based equilibrium model explains these empirical findings.
ER  - 

