T1  - Ex-Dividend Profitability and Institutional Trading Skill
AU  - HENRY, TYLER R.
AU  - KOSKI, JENNIFER L.
Y1  - 2017/02/01
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12472
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 461
EP  - 494
VL  - 72
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12472
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We use institutional trading data to examine whether skilled institutions exploit positive abnormal ex-dividend returns. Results show that institutions concentrate trading around certain ex-dates, and earn higher profits around these events. Dividend capture trades represent 6% of all institutional buy trades but contribute 15% of overall abnormal returns. Institutional dividend capture trading is persistent. Institutional ex-day profitability is also strongly cross-sectionally related to trade execution skill. The relation between execution skill and profits disappears around placebo non-ex-days. Results suggest that skilled institutions target certain opportunities rather than benefiting uniformly over time. Furthermore, only skilled institutions can profit from dividend capture.
ER  - 

